mmisw. bcodmo.description:
The Biological and Chemical Oceanography Data Management Office (BCO-DMO) is funded by the US National Science Foundation Division of Ocean Sciences to work with ocean biogeochemistry researchers in the US to improve access to data resulting from their respective programs.  In an effort to improve data access, BCO-DMO staff members are collaborating with researchers from the Tetherless World Constellation (TWC) at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (RPI) to develop an ontology that formally describes the concepts and relationships in the data managed by the BCO-DMO.  Version 2.0 (February 2011) of the BCO Ontology is still a work in progress.  Development is ongoing, with much work still remaining to be done on the parameter class.

Version 2.0 is being shared in it's current state in hopes that community members may find the work done thus far to be useful for their projects.  We welcome feedback and comments on the content.

Development of the ontology has been guided by a use case based approach.  The use cases were derived from data access related requests received from members of the research community served by the BCO-DMO.  The resultant BCO Ontology represents the information stored in the metadata database and satisfies the requirements of the use cases.  The BCO-DMO metadata database currently contains information that powers several different user and machine-to-machine interfaces to the BCO-DMO data repositories.  One goal of the ontology development project is to enable subsequent development of semantically-enabled components (e.g. faceted search) to enhance the power of those interfaces and improve data access through enhanced data discovery.
mmisw. bcodmo.name: Biological and Chemical Oceanography

mmisw.1599542533.description: The classification is a framework for organizing knowledge about coasts and oceans and their living systems. It provides a structure for synthesizing data so that habitats can be characterized and reported in a standard way, and information can be aggregated and evaluated across the national landscape and seascape. Building on existing classification efforts and informed by a series of technical meetings and workshops, the CMECS framework integrates the current state of knowledge about ecological and habitat classification. The result is an ecosystem-oriented, science-based framework for the identification, inventory, and description of coastal and marine habitats and biodiversity.

Applying an operation to a quantity results in a new quantity that frequently has different units than the original quantity. The CSDMS semantic work has a goal of automated semantic mediation, matching or reconciliation. mmisw.4157839049.description: The Assumption terms from the CSDMS project, represented as an OWL resource. An Assumption is not a  part of a CSDMS Standard Name; rather, it is used to describe a model or its parameters in detail. (Hence, an assumption should not be used to evaluate parameter matches in a simplistic way.) An Assumption is a broad term that can include things like conditions, simplifications, approximations, limitations, conventions, provisos and other forms of clarification. CSDMS encourages model developers to include as many <assume> tags in their Model Coupling Metadata (MCM) file as they feel apply to their model or its particular input or output variable; XML tag nesting determines the scope of an <assume> tag. The CSDMS semantic work has a goal of automated semantic mediation, matching or reconciliation. While the focus is on a 'lingua franca', the standard names are often built from a hierarchical set of concepts, and may eventually be used to construct a type of ontology.
mmisw.4157839049.name: CSDMS Assumption Terms

mmisw.4174490154.description: Terms describing plots developed by NOAA NMFS PFEL. The plots in this data group are of monthly means in 1-degree lat/lon squares of sea surface temperature and anomalies. They were computed from GTS surface observations received twice a day by PFEL from FNMOC (Fleet Numerical Meteorology and Oceanography Center). These are global real-time surface observations from platforms such as ships and buoys (both fixed and drifting). They are a subset of the data which will be included in an update to COADS (Comprehensive Ocean-Atmosphere Data Set, also see COADS on CD-ROM) .
mmisw.4174490154.name: Sea Surface Temperature (Global Telecommunications Systems, GTS)

mmisw.digoi.description:
The University of Trento is conducting a study for the European Commission on the relevant initiatives in the area of digital object and author identifiers (short name: DIGOIDUNA). One of the key tool provided to the community is this ontology.

The aim of providing this model is twofold. First of all, the model captures the relevant entities in the domain under investigation and the relationships between these entities according to the proposed dimensions of analysis (i.e. feature matrices and themes).  In this respect, the model helps to understand the complexity of the dynamics that are in play in our domain of study by representing the entire spectrum of features, interdependencies and dimensions that we considered relevant in our analysis. 
Secondly, it represents a useful working instrument which allows policy makers to use the proposed dimensions of analysis to assess the impact of adopting a particular scheme or system by crossing multiple dimensions  (both at the system and the schema level) and considering their effect on different stakeholders. Moreover, the ontology may become a flexible collaborative framework that can be extended during the course of the present investigation but that can also be improved as result of external contributions in future.
mmisw.digoi.name: digoiduna

mmisw.hls.description: Human Localization Sensor Ontology (HLS) is OWL2 DL ontology, based on SSN ontology, describing knowledge in human localization sensing patterns using description logics (SROIQ) as defined classes, allowing automatic classification (i.e. semantic sensor search) of sensors that can be used to find human location.
